Introduction¶

In this study, we are looking into analysing bike sharing data. The data sets include information about individual rides made in Ford GoBike bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area as well as Mobibikes system covering Vancouver, BC area. The purpose of this study is to answer some general questions about the bike sharing in these 2 cities and find out the users behaviour during 2019 to account for seasonal changes. Year 2020 turned out to be an unusual year with COVID-19 pandemic happening and there is anecdotal information that bike riding in general increased because of the pandemic. It would be interesting to investigate this via the data available for 2020 given the data only accounts for the first 4 months of 2020. It should be noted that this data represents the bike sharing usage and the ultimate results may not be representative of the actual overall biking behaviour since the bike users may tend to avoid using shared equipment due to concern over infection and instead utilize personal bikes. Nevertheless, we look into this in hope to find some insight

Gathering Data¶

  • The data for San Francisco is downloaded from: https://www.lyft.com/bikes/bay-wheels/system-data

  • The data for Vancouver is downloaded from: https://www.mobibikes.ca/en/system-data

Looking at some basic definitions

Having a large number of outliers shown in the box plot, it is reasonable to drop the outlier larger than Q3 + 1.5 x IQR Let us calculate this for this dataset

In [41]:
# Calculating the quantiles the the top cut off duration_sec
df_san_clean_large_duration = df_san_clean.duration_sec.quantile([0.25,0.75])
df_san_clean_IRQ = df_san_clean_large_duration[0.75] - df_san_clean_large_duration[0.25]
time_top_cutoff = df_san_clean_large_duration[0.75] + 1.5 * df_san_clean_IRQ

Visualizing Data¶

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 2.9 millions entries in the San Francisco data base with 8 features (duration_sec, start_time, end_time, user_type, time_of_day, day_of_week, month_of_year and year) and 0.7 million entries in the Vancouver data base with 7 features similar to the features of San Francisco except time_of_day as we could not extract this from the available data.

the start_time, end_time are datetime type, duration_sec is numerical, and the rest are categorical features.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The main features of interest are time_of_day, day_of_week, or month_of_year and year to explore the user's behavior. We are also interested in duration_sec to check how long the trips took and user_type to see if there was any dependency on the user membership.

Since we are also interested in the possible change due to COVID-19 in 2020, we will be also looking into yearly changes in some of these features

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

All above could be equally important, and we would need to explore and find out the relations. One particular matter is the effect of the pandemic into bike usages which will come out when we do yearly comparison

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

Looking at the duration_sec, both data sets appear to be highly right skewed which suggested that a log x-scale transformation might be helpful. Performing the log10 scale transformation shows that the distribution for both are Log-normal. This is helpful to know for the case where we would need to do modelling and prediction, however that is not the intent here

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

When comparing the data between the two cities, it appears that San Francisco has higher number of rides which is normal given the population difference between the two cities. However, it appears that the Vancouver riders were using the bikes for longer duration in average.

The other interesting finding is that the average ride duration remained relatively constant for Vancouver from 2019 to 2020 with a slight increase. However, San Francisco showed a more significant increase in average ride duration in 2020.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

There are several observations from the plots seen above

  1. In both cities the duration of the rides was greater in the weekend and in general Vancouverite took longer rides
  2. The duration of the rides are fairly even for San Franciscan throughout the year, but Vancouverite seem to ride longer in the dry season. Given the rainy nature of City of Vancouver, this is an expected trend
  3. San Franciscan tend to have longer trips during the afternoon hours and customers tend to go for longer trips than the subscribers in this city
  4. Vancouver has a much more complex pass structure than San Francisco and the single trip pass holders tend to go for longer rides in Vancouver.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

  1. Despite the customer membership types going for longer rides in San Francisco they account for much smaller number of trips
  2. In San Francisco Jan, Feb, and Mar account for the highest number of the trips with Feb being the most popular time to ride
  3. San Francisco data also shows a very large drop in use of the bikes for subscribers in 2020 where the customer type usage does not seem to have changed much from 2019 to 2020. This is due to less data collection in 2020
  4. First 4 months of 2020 shows an increase in using the bikes in general in San Francisco however there is not any major change in 2020 usage in Vancouver.
  5. San Francisco data also shows a major drop in the number of bike rides in the weekends for 2019; however, this drop is less pronounced in 2020. The lower height of the bars for 2020 is due to less data collection since we only have the data for the first 4 months of 2020.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

Plotting the histograms table shows that regardless of what year, month, or day of week, majority of the trips were under 2000 seconds in San Francisco while the trips in Vancouver tend to stretch into 4000 seconds mark.

Another finding is that the non-subscriber/member user types seem to have a larger variance in the trip duration for both cities while the subscribers tend to go for more consistent ride duration which might mean they probably use it for some fixed trip length such as commute to work and back

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

The non-members riding on the weekends tend to go for the longest trips, especially in San Francisco.

Another interesting finding is that, in 2020, duration of the rides increased by about 7% in San Francisco however there is no such an obvious change for Vancouver.
